</p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:normal; font-weight:bold">Q618 </span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mr Ruffley:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> How was it proposed to evidence that?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Barry Tootell</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">robably </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">since </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2011 we have been running with a board risk appetite</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was to have a minimum level of core tier 1 of 10% in order to satisfy ourselves on our capital position for the future. We accepted it was a timeline to get there and it was</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t going to be an overnight fix, but 10% was our board appetite for capital adequacy. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">That was the plan that we were working towards on a standalone basis. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">That was also one of the underpins in considering the Lloyds transaction. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">That was our board’s view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span sty